-  Polymer Infiltration and Pyrolysis (PIP), where the UHTC phase is added to a SiC precursor [9,10]. Usually, up to ten successive infiltration cycles followed by a respective pyrolysis step are required to obtain a dense matrix;
-  Reactive Melt Infiltration (RMI), where the carbon preforms are first impregnated  with  B-containing  phases  (e.g  ZrB2  and  elemental  B powders)  and  then  infiltrated  with  Zr-containing  melts  in  special furnaces [11]. The reaction between Zr-based melt and B powders leads  to  formation  of  further  ZrB2,  but  leaves  notable  fraction  of unreacted metal;
- Chemical Vapour Infiltration (CVI) with gaseous precursors of carbide phases, or with C precursors preceded by an infiltration stage with a UHTC containing slurry [12,13];
-  Radio frequency - Chemical Vapour Infiltration (RF-CVI), a variant of conventional CVI where high values of matrix density are achieved in hours rather than weeks [14,15]
