3. FE model description
- (a) transient thermal fluxes, simulating the test conditions and coming from computational fluid dynamics (CFD) calculations [16], have been applied on the exposed external surfaces;
- (b) radiation conditions have been applied on all the external surfaces. The radiation to the environment has been simulated by employing the ANSYS AUX12 radiation matrix method. See the ANSYS reference manual [13] for further details;
- (c) adiabatic conditions have been applied over the interface between the AISI 304 flange and the model support system;
- (d) the initial temperature, that is, the temperature at the begin of the re-entry trajectory, has been assumed to be equal to 300K;
- (e) thermal contacts at all interfaces have been considered as perfect, that is, all the interfaces have been assumed glued.
It is important to spend some words on the heat flux distribution applied on the FE model.
The change in manufacturing process passing from coupon level to subcomponent level makes it very difficult to determine some experimental parameters which are needed in numerical computations. One of these experimental parameters is the catalysis of the UHTC. Hence, in order to verify the influence of catalysis on the thermal behaviour of the nose cap, both the noncatalytic wall (NCW) model and the finite rate catalysis (FRC) one have been used to compute heat fluxes acting on its external surface. The following conditions were also considered in the CFD computation:
